    <bioghist encodinganalog="545">
      <p>Brightmoor in Redford Township was originally a housing subdivision opened in 1922 and situated on Grand River Avenue approximately one mile from the city limits of Detroit. The area rapidly developed, and in 1926, the area was annexed by the city of Detroit. The beginning of Episcopal church services in Brightmoor can be traced to a "church on wheels" driven by the Rev. W.F. Jerome. Later that same year of 1923, the first recorded Episcopal Church service was held in the Brightmoor Community Hall. The congregation moved again in 1923 to the Maccabee Hall on Burt Road. Then in 1924, St. James Mission (as the church was named) erected its own building on Burt Road.</p>
      <p>The church grew rapidly and there was need for further expansion. But not until after World War II were plans made for a new church building to be located at West Outer Drive and Lahser. The building was completed in 1951 and St. James became a parish church with the signing of corporation papers.</p>
      <p>At one time St. James had a membership of 1600 members, but this dropped to 140 in 1988. Because of declining membership and the cost of maintaining the facility, St. James disbanded early in 1993.</p>
    </bioghist>
    <scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
      <p>The records of St. James parish include vestry minutes, 1924-1993; baptism, confirmation, marriage, and burial records, 1926-1993; bulletins, administrative records; records of the Episcopal Church Women and other parish organizations; and photographs. This record group has been divided into nine series covering the period from 1923 soon after the church began conducting services until 1993 when the church members decided to disband.</p>
    </scopecontent>
